  <td BGCOLOR="#FFEA18"><img src="yerspestisb.jpg" width="600" height="24"><p><center>
    <b><font size=+1>Lecture 16.&nbsp; Tuberculosis.</font></b>
</center>
<br>
<img src="yerspestisc.jpg" width="600" height="24"></td>
</tr></table></center>
<p><table width="600" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0">
  <tr>
    <td bgcolor="#99CCCC">"Tuberculosis" is a relatively modern name (first
appearing in print in the 1840s) for a very old disease.&nbsp; It comes
from the Latin word, <i>tuberculum</i>, meaning "protuberance, projection
or growth," and refers to the tumor-like nodules that victims often display.&nbsp;
In fact, until TB's bacterial agent was discovered in 1882, many physicians
thought TB's characteristic nodules and wasting identified it as a form
of cancer.
<p>Patients suffering from TB exhibited many symptoms:&nbsp;
evening fever, night sweats, blood spitting, weak pulse, diarrhea....&nbsp;
But the symptom that left the strongest impression was emaciation.&nbsp;
It is this characteristic that formed the basis of TB's many names:
<ul>
<li>
"Phthisis" (pronounced TIE-sis, or THIGH-sis) from
the Greek word <i>phthiein</i>, meaning "to waste away."&nbsp; Hippocrates
used this term to describe the wasting and melting away of a patient's
body caused by disease of the lungs.&nbsp; Many patients diagnosed with
phthisis were probably victims of tuberculosis.</li>
</ul>

<ul>
<li>
<font color="#000000">"Tabes" (pronounced TAY-beez) from the Latin word
<i>tabere</i>, meaning "to waste away."&nbsp; Tabes was used to describe
the wasting effects of many diseases from syphilis to cancer.</font></li>
</ul>

<ul>
<li>
<font color="#000000">"Consumption" from the Latin word <i>consumere</i>,
meaning "to use up, eat, or waste."&nbsp; This vivid term became a popular
way to describe the condition of tuberculous patients.</font></li>
</ul>
<font color="#000000">With the advent of firsthand anatomical study and
autopsy in the Renaissance, physicians found that the wasting of phthisis
was always associated with curious lesions in the inner organs.&nbsp; They
called these nodules "tubercles."</font><font color="#000000">&nbsp;</font>
<p><font color="#000000">Tubercles varied in their consistency.&nbsp; They
could be as hard as cartilage and bone, or crumbly like chalk.&nbsp; In
some cases, they were found to be filled with pus having the consistency
of cheese or honey.</font><font color="#000000"></font>
<p><font color="#000000">As anatomical information grew, so did physicians'
questions about tubercles:</font>
<ul>
<li>
<font color="#000000">How do tubercles arise?</font></li>
</ul>

<ul>
<li>
<font color="#000000">Are they present already in the body and just get
damaged and enlarged by disease?</font></li>
</ul>

<ul>
<li>
<font color="#000000">Or, are they new features formed by the disease?</font></li>
</ul>

<ul>
<li>
<font color="#000000">Are all of these different forms of tubercles related?</font></li>
</ul>

<ul>
<li>
<font color="#000000">Or, are they manifestations of completely different
kinds of disease (like the spots of measles, chickenpox, smallpox, syphilis....)</font></li>
</ul>
<font color="#000000">Like Alzheimer's today, the internal physical effects
of developing TB could only be studied after the victim's death.</font><font color="#000000">&nbsp;</font>
<p><font color="#000000">This changed with the introduction of two new
diagnostic procedures:</font>
<ul>
<li>
<font color="#000000"><b>percussion</b> (1761) by Austrian, <b>Leopold
von Auenbrugger (1722-1809)</b>, who noticed that tapping the thorax produces
different sounds depending on the location being struck; von Auenbrugger
learned to interpret the tones produced by <b>striking the chest with massed
tips of the fingers</b>; he used this method to detect fluid and other
matter in the lungs.</font></li>
</ul>

<ul>
<li>
<font color="#000000"><b>indirect auscultation</b> (1816) by French-born,
<b>Ren&eacute; La&euml;nnec (1781-1826)</b>, who found that direct <i>auscultation</i>
(listening to internal bodily sounds by putting one's ear directly on a
patient's chest) was problematic, especially when treating a female patient,
or one infested with vermin; La&euml;nnec rolled up a card and discovered
he could hear the sounds better than by direct auscultation; he improved
on this simple concept and named the new instrument the <b>stethoscope</b>,
from the Greek words <i>stethos</i>, meaning "chest," and <i>skopein</i>,
meaning "to see."</font></li>
</ul>
<p><center><table BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=15 COLS=1 WIDTH=440 BGCOLOR="#5DBACA" >
<tr>
<td bgcolor="#003333">
<center><img SRC="tblaennecroom.jpg" BORDER=5 height=463 width=400>
</center></td>
</tr>
</table></center>
<font color="#000000">&nbsp;</font>
<p><center>
<font color="#000000">____________</font></center>
<font color="#000000"></font>
<p><font color="#000000">Because the symptoms of tuberculosis were so varied
and there was little agreement as to its cause (even after the <i>tubercle
bacillus</i> was isolated by Robert Koch (1843-1910) in 1882, physicians
treated their patients with an array of nonspecific healthful remedies:&nbsp;
fresh air, sunshine, good nutrition, sufficient sleep, and exercise.</font>
<center><table BORDER=0 CELLSPACING=0 CELLPADDING=10 COLS=1 WIDTH=280 BGCOLOR="#5DBACA" >
